  <span id="freeText16328116209659874089" style="display:none">I have read this torn, twenty-five year old copy three times now. No easy feet, as it is one of the thicker michener books. The first time I read it, Iwanted to convert to Judaism and go to Israel and live on a kibbutz. I wanted to dig in the dirt and find relics and artifacts that would confirm the existence of God. I wanted to be a part of the spirit that was behind the community of believers, scientists, anthropologists. The educated and strong. I wanted to get tan and lean and smart and worldly.<br />This book did that for me. The second time I read it, I was less idealistic, more pragmatic. I saw the history as a back drop for the love story. <br />The third time i wanted to travel to Israel and see the Holy Land, not to dig in, but just to dig.<br />This book is one of the top three books on my list. I have never read any other Michener, but i hear he is good. I only needed this one.</span>
